<h3>
    Part 1: Falling Object
</h3>
<p>
    A person drops an object move mass \( m \) from a cliff of height \( y_0 \) as depicted below.
    Consider the height = 0 point to be the ground.
</p>
<img src = '/podAssets/energy/conservation_of_energy_quantitative/vertical_dropped.jpg' height = '300px' width = 'auto'/>
<ol class = 'questionList'>
    <li class = 'question'>
        Write a symbolic formula for the <strong>Total Energy</strong>
        of the object-earth system in terms of the variables stated at several different points:
        <ol type = 'a' class = 'subQuestionList'>
            <li class="subQuestion" data-answer = '\( \text{Energy} = m g y_i \)'>
                Immediately after the mass is dropped,
                when its height is \( y_i \) and it has no speed.
            </li>
            <li class = 'subQuestion' data-answer = '\( \text{Energy} = \frac{1}{2}m g y_i + \frac{1}{2} m v_{\text{half}}^2 \)'>
                When the mass is halfway down its fall.
                Its height is half the original height and its speed is
                defined as
                \( v_{\text{half}} \).
            </li>
            <li class = 'subQuestion' data-answer = '\( \text{Energy} = \frac{1}{2} m v_{\text{max}}^2 \)'>
                Immediately before the mass strikes the ground.
                At this point, the height is 0 and its speed is \( v_{\text{max}} \).
            </li>
        </ol>
    </li>
    <li class = 'question' data-answer = '\( mg y_i = \frac{1}{2}m g y_i + \frac{1}{2} m v_{\text{half}}^2 = \frac{1}{2} m v_{\text{max}}^2 \); This equation is true because no work is done on the object-earth system,
        and so the total energy of the system is equal at all points.'>
        All of the values for total energy of the object-earth system determined above are equal
        because no work is done on the system.
        When inventing a new formula, it is absolutely crucial that you <emph>explicitly</emph> cite
        the laws of science that make this formula valid.
        To this end, please write a new equation that sets
        all the values above equal and copy the statement "Because no work is done on the object-earth system"
        next to your formula.
    </li>
    <li class = 'question'>
        Use the equality determined above to identify new formulas for key quantities in this situation:
        <ol type = 'a' class = 'subQuestionList'>
            <li class = 'subQuestion' data-answer = '\( v_{\text{max}} = \sqrt{2 g y_i} \)'>
                Derive a formula for \( v_{\text{max}} \) in terms of \( y_i \) and \( g \), the free-fall acceleration on the planet.
                Prove that your formula is dimensionally correct.
            </li>
            <li class="subQuestion" data-answer = '\( v_{\text{half}} = \sqrt{g y_i} \)'>
                Derive a formula for \( v_{\text{half}} \) in terms of \( y_i \) and \( g \).
                Prove that your formula is dimensionally correct.
            </li>
            <li class="subQuestion" data-answer = ' \( v_{\text{half}} = \frac{v_{\text{max}}}{\sqrt{2}} \)'>
                Using the two formula above, derive a variable for \( v_{\text{half}} \) in terms of \( v_{\text{max}} \).
            </li>
            <li class="subQuestion">
                Student A looks at this problem, and says "The ball gets faster as it goes down. When the ball has fallen halfway down, it must be going at half its maximum speed."
                What elements of student A's reasoning are correct? What elements of student A's reasoning are incorrect? How do you know.
            </li>
        </ol>
    </li>
</ol>
