<h3>
    Part 2: Object Thrown Directly Upward
</h3>
<p>
    A person throws some ball of mass \( m \) vertically upward at a speed \( v_i \).
    When he throws it, the ball is at a vertical position \( y_i \).
    Ignore air resistance and assume that no work is done on the ball-earth system.
    Please consider height = 0 to be the ground.
</p>
<img src = '/podAssets/energy/conservation_of_energy_quantitative/vertical_thrown_up.jpg' height = '300px' width = 'auto'/>
<ol class="questionList">
    <li class="question">
        Write an expression for the total energy of the ball-earth system at
        several different points in terms of the variables stated.
        Note that the kinetic energy formula includes speed, not velocity,
        because it does not depend upon the direction the ball is moving.
        Thus, an ball moving up and an object moving down at the same speed have the same kinetic energy.
        <ol type = 'a' class="subQuestionList">
            <li class="subQuestion" data-answer = '\( \text{Energy} = \frac{1}{2} m v_i^2 + m g y_i \)'>
                When the ball is first let go.
            </li>
            <li class="subQuestion" data-answer = '\( \text{Energy} =  m g y_{\text{max}} \)'>
                When the ball is at its highest point.
                At this point, it is momentarily stopped (speed = 0)
                and its height is given by \( y_{\text{max}} \).
            </li>
            <li class="subQuestion" data-answer = '\( \text{Energy} =  \frac{1}{2} m v_c^2 + m g y_i \)'>
                When the ball falls back past the point it was let go.
                It returns to its initial height, and has a speed \( v_c \)
            </li>
            <li class="subQuestion" data-answer = '\( \text{Energy} = \frac{1}{2} m v_{\text{max}}^2 \)'>
                Immediately before the ball strikes the ground.
                At this point, its vertical position is 0 and its speed is given by \( v_{\text{max}} \).
            </li>
        </ol>
    </li>
    <li class="question" data-answer = '\( \frac{1}{2} m v_i^2 + m g y_i =  m g y_{\text{max}} = \frac{1}{2} m v_{\text{max}}^2 \) This equation is true because no work is done on the ball-earth system,
        and thus the total energy of the system remains constant according to
        the Law of Conservation of Energy.'>
        Connect these expressions to create an equation
        based on the conservation of energy.
        State explicitly why this equation is true.
        Remove any redundant pieces of your equation.
    </li>
    <li class="question">
        Use the equation above to derive new formulas for key quantities:
        <ol type = 'a' class="subQuestionList">
            <li class="subQuestion" data-answer = '\( y_{\text{max}} = \frac{v_i^2}{2g} + y_i \)'>
                Determine a formula for \( y_{\text{max}} \) in terms of \( y_i \), \( v_i \),
                and \( g \).
                Prove your formula is dimensionally correct.
            </li>
            <li class="subQuestion" data-answer = '\( v_c = v_i \); The speed is identical when it reaches the initial point.'>
                Determine a formula for \( v_c \) in terms of \( v_i \).
                Remember that these variables are both <emph>speed</emph> and not <emph>velocity</emph>.
                Argue your formula is intuitive.
            </li>
            <li class="subQuestion" data-answer = '\( v_{\text{max}} = \sqrt{v_i^2 + 2 g y_i} \)'>
                Determine a formula for \( v_{\text{max}} \) in terms of \( y_i \), \( v_i \), and \( g \).
                Prove your formula is dimensionally correct.
            </li>
        </ol>
    </li>
    <li class="question">
        Consider a special case in which \( v_i = 0 \).
        This would represent a situation in which the person did not throw the ball upward at all,
        but simply dropped it. This case is actually identical to the previous situation,
        so if you plug in the value \( v_i = 0 \), you should receive the same values as before.
        <ol class="subQuestionList" type = 'a'>
            <li class="subQuestion" data-answer = 'You find \( y_{\text{max}} = y_i \), meaning that the ball, if dropped, does not rise higher than its initial height.'>
                Using the formula you derived above, determine the value of \( y_{\text{max}} \)
                in the special case that \( v_i = 0 \).
                Argue that this value makes sense.
            </li>
            <li class="subQuestion" data-answer = 'You find \( v_{\text{max}} = \sqrt{2 g y_i } \), identically to above.'>
                Using the formula derived above, determine the value of \( v_{\text{max}} \)
                in the special case that \( v_i = 0 \).
                Show that this is equal to the same value you determined in a previous problem
                for a ball that is dropped from a height \( y_i \).
            </li>
        </ol>
    </li>
</ol>

